ayer was minimal. In January 2011, he contracted [[necrotizing fasciitis]], which severely restricted his ability to perform. He appeared publicly with the band on only one known occasion, playing two songs during an encore at one of Slayer's Big 4 performances in April 2011; he also attended rehearsals for [[Fun Fun Fun Fest]] in November 2011, but did not end up performing at this show. By July 2012, Hanneman had not written or recorded any new material for the band's follow up to 2009's ''World Painted Blood''.<ref>{{cite web| last = Appleford| first = Steve| title = Slayer Ramp Up Work on New Album| work = [[Rolling Stone]]| publisher = [[Wenner Media]]| date = July 6, 2012| url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/slayer-ramp-up-work-on-new-album-20120706| accessdate = July 7, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title = Slayer's Kerry King Talks Upcoming Album, Jeff Hanneman's Health In New Video Interview| work = [[Blabbermouth.net]]| publisher = [[Roadrunner Records]]| date = July 5, 2012| url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=176373| accessdate = July 7, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| last = Ramirez| first = Carlos| title = Slayer Release Statement Updating the Health Status of Jeff Hanneman| work = [[Noisecreep]]| publisher = [[AOL]]| date = May 1, 2012| url = http://www.noisecreep.com/2012/05/01/slayer-jeff-hanneman/| accessdate = July 7, 2012}}</ref> In February 2013, Kerry King stated he was planning on recording all of the guitar parts for the upcoming album himself, but was open to Hanneman's return if he was willing and able. King also denied that [[Gary Holt (musician)|Gary Holt]], member of [[Exodus (American band)|Exodus]] and Hanneman's live fill-in, would write or record anything for the upcoming album.<ref>{{cite web| title = Kerry King Talks New Slayer Album, Jeff Hanneman's Health Status (Video)| work = [[Blabbermouth.net]]| publisher = [[Roadrunner Records]]| date = February 1, 2013| url = http://www.blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=185694| accessdate = February 1, 2013}}</ref> Hanneman died on May 2, 2013 at the age of 49 due to liver failure.<ref>{{cite web| author = Billboard Staff| title = Slayer Guitarist Jeff Hanneman Dead at 49| work = [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]| date = May 2, 2013| url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1560534/slayer-guitarist-jeff-hanneman-dead-at-49| accessdate = May 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last=McIver|first=Joel|title=The Bloody Reign of Slayer|year=2008|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|isbn=978-0-85712-038-0|authorlink=Joel McIver}}\n*{{cite book|last=Ferris|first=D.X.|title=[[Reign in Blood]]|series=[[33\u2153]] Series|year=2008|publisher=[[Continuum Books]]|isbn=978-0-8264-2909-4}}\n*{{cite book|last=Szubrycht|first=Jaros\u0142aw|title=Bez lito\u015bci. Prawdziwa historia zespo\u0142u Slayer (No mercy. The true history of Slayer)|year=2006|publisher=Kagra|isbn=83-87598-48-8}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q131231|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|s=no|wikt=no}}\n* {{Official website}}\n{{Slayer|state=expanded}}\n{{Featured article}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Portal bar|Los Angeles}}\n\n[[Category:Slayer| ]]\n[[Category:1981 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:American thrash metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Articles which contain graphical timelines]]\n[[Category:Def Jam Recordings artists]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Kerrang! Awards winners]]\n[[Category:Metal Blade Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 2019]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1981]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Musical quartets]]\n[[Category:Nuclear Blast artists]]\n[[Category:Obscenity controversies in music]]\n[[Category:Thrash metal musical groups from California]]\n", "name_user": "189.62.148.238", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slayer"}
{"title_page": "Magdeburg Hauptbahnhof", "text_new": "{{Infobox station\n| name= Magdeburg Hauptbahnhof \n| symbol              = rail\n| symbol2             = s\n| symbol_location     = de\n| symbol_location2    = \n| image= Magdeburger Bahnhof.jpg\n| caption= Entrance hall\n| type= Through station\n| platforms= 10\n| passengers= 40,000\n| trains= \n| code          = {{Deutsche Bahn station codes|code=3881<ref name =categories/>|ds100=LM<ref name=Eisenbahnatlas >{{cite book|title=Eisenbahnatlas Deutschland (German railway atlas) | edition=2009/2010 |publisher= Schweers + Wall | year= 2009 |isbn= 978-3-89494-139-0}}</ref>|ibnr=8010224|category=2<ref name =categories >{{DBCatsURL}}</ref>}}\n| opened              = {{Start date and age|1873|05|15|df=y}}\n| closed              =\n| electrified         = 1923-1946<ref>Since 1946 catenaries and overhead line masts were dismantled as Soviet war reparations.</ref><br/>{{Start date and age|1957|01|06|df=y}}\n| architect= Ludwig Heim\n| address       = [[Magdeburg]], [[Saxony-Anhalt]]\n| country       = Germany\n| coordinates= {{coord|52|7|50|N|11|37|40|E|region:DE-ST_type:railwaystation|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| line= \n* [[Berlin-Potsdam-Magdeburg Railway|Berlin\u2013Magdeburg]] (km 141.8)\n* [[Magdeburg-Wittenberge railway|Magdeburg\u2013Wittenberge]] (km 0.0)\n* [[Magdeburg-Leipziger railway|Magdeburg\u2013Leipzig]] (km 0.0)\n* [[Braunschweig\u2013Magdeburg railway|Braunschweig\u2013Magdeburg]] (km 141.8)\n* [[Magdeburg\u2013Thale railway|Magdeburg\u2013Thale / Blankenburg (Harz)]] (km 0.0)\n| website             = [https://www.bahnhof.de/bahnhof-de/bahnhof/Magdeburg_Hbf-1027886 www.bahnhof.de]\n| map_type            = Saxony-Anhalt#Germany#Europe\n| map_caption         = Location within Saxony-Anhalt##Location within Germany##Location within Europe\n| embedded            = {{Infobox mapframe\n| stroke-colour       = #C60C30\n| stroke-width        = 3\n| marker              = rail-underground\n| marker-colour       = #009D58\n| zoom                = 15\n}}\n| services     =\n{{s-rail|title=DB Fernverkehr}}\n{{S-line|system=DB-IC|line=55|previous=Braunschweig|next=K\u00f6then|type=South|}}\n{{s-line|system=DB-IC|line=56|previous=Helmstedt|next=Halle (Saale)|type=Norddeich Mole|type2=Leipzig|rows1=2}}\n{{s-line|system=DB-IC|line=56|previous=Helmstedt|next=Brandenburg|type=Norddeich Mole|type2=Cottbus|hide1=yes}}\n{{s-rail|title=Abellio Rail Mitteldeutschland}}\n{{s-line|system=RE-SA|line=6|previous=Magdeburg-Neustadt|next=}}\n{{s-line|system=RE-SA|line=10|previous=Magdeburg-Buckau|next=}}\n{{s-line|system=RE-SA|line=11|previous=Magdeburg-Buckau|next=}}\n{{s-line|system=RE-SA|line=21|previous=Magdeburg-Buckau|next=}}\n{{s-line|system=RE-SA|line=31|previous=Magdeburg-Buckau|next=}}\n{{s-line|system=RB-SA|line=36|previous=Magdeburg-Neustadt|next=}}\n{{s-line|system=RB-SA|line=41|previous=Magdeburg-Buckau|next=}}\n{{s-line|system=RB-SA|line=43|previous=Magdeburg-Buckau|next=}}\n{{s-line|system=RB-SA|line=48|previous=|next=Magdeburg-Buckau}}\n{{s-rail|title=DB Regio Nordost}}\n{{s-line|system=RE-BB|line=1|previous=|next=Magdeburg-Neustadt}}\n{{s-rail|title=DB Regio S\u00fcdost}}\n{{s-line|system=RE-SA|line=13|previous=|next=Magdeburg-Neustadt}}\n{{s-line|system=RE-SA|line=20|previous=Magdeburg-Neustadt|next=}}\n{{s-line|system=RE-SA|line=30|previous=|next=Magdeburg-Buckau}}\n{{s-line|system=RB-SA|line=40|previous=Magdeburg-Sudenburg|next=Magdeburg-Neustadt}}\n{{s-line|system=RB-SA|line=42|previous=|next=Magdeburg-Neustadt}}\n{{s-rail|title=S-Bahn Mittelelbe}}\n{{s-line|system=MESB|line=1|previous=Magdeburg-Hasselbachplatz|next=Magdeburg-Neustadt}}\n| other_services      = \n}}\n\n'''Magdeburg Hauptbahnhof''' (German for Magdeburg main station, sometimes translated as '''Magdeburg Central Station''') is the main railway station in the city of [[Magdeburg]] in the northern part of the German state of [[Saxony-Anhalt]].\n\n==Importance ==\nThe station is the main station of Magdeburg and along with [[Halle (Saale) Hauptbahnhof|Halle Hauptbahnhof]] the centre of long-distance rail transport in Saxony-Anhalt. It is also connected to the [[Magdeburg S-Bahn]] network and the [[HarzElbeExpress]] regional rail network.\n\n==History ==\nThe current main station is built on the site of the western side of the former Magdeburg Fortress. Several competing railway companies had built lines to Magdeburg between 1839 and 1849, each with their own stations. They were built on the west bank of the [[Elbe]] river, on reclaimed land. With the increasing industrialisation and growing importance of Magdeburg, the need for space at stations grew. A central station, however, was not feasible at first.\n\nAs the existing railway facilities in Magdeburg became more inadequate the construction of a central station became more urgent. Both the city of Magdeburg and various railway companies conducted lengthy negotiations with the military with the objective of buying the grounds of the disused fortress. In 1870, three railway companies, the [[Berlin-Potsdam-Magdeburg Railway]], the [[Magdeburg-Halberstadt Railway]], [[Magdeburg-Leipzig Railway]] finally reached an agreement to buy the 33 hectares of the fortifications from the state of [[Prussia]].<ref>{{cite book | first= Helmut|last= Asmus | title= 1200 Jahre Magdeburg (1200 years of Magdeburg) | volume= 3 | publisher=Scriptum | location=Magdeburg | year =2005 | pages=222\u2013223 |language=German }}</ref>\n\n===Construction ===\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 102-00996, Magdeburg, Frontk\u00e4mpfertag.jpg|thumb|left|Former western station building and concourse (January 1925) - now ''K\u00f6lner Platz'']]\nThe foundation stone for the new Magdeburg station was laid in 1870. The companies involved were the Berlin-Potsdam-Magdeburg Railway, the Magdeburg-Halberstadt Railway, both of which had been strongly affected by the confined spaces of the stations on the banks of the Elbe, and lastly, the Magdeburg-Leipzig Railway which was less troubled by its existing infrastructure.\n\nThe companies built two entrance buildings. The Magdeburg-Leipzig Railway constructed the eastern entrance building in the style of a [[Tuscany|Tuscan]] palace between 1872 and 1882. Its cladding consists of [[sandstone]] obtained from [[K\u00f6nigslutter]]. The western entrance building was built by the Berlin-Potsdam-Magdeburg Railway and was shared with the Magdeburg-Halberstadt Railway. In contrast to the eastern building, [[Nebra (Unstrut)|Nebra]] sandstone was used for the north facade of the western building, its walls were made of bricks faced with stone. Both buildings were of equal length and connected with each other by separate tunnels for passengers and baggage.\n\nOn 15 May 1873 the first train ran between the new station and the town of [[Burg bei Magdeburg|Burg]]. The official opening took place on 18 August 1873. Construction works continued until 1893. In addition to the passenger station there were also extensive freight facilities.\n \nOn 1 July 1923 the first electric train ran from Zerbst to Magdeburg Hauptbahnhof. Electrification had begun in 1910, but had been interrupted by [[World War I]]. From 7 October 1934 electric trains also ran to Halle.\n\n===Damage in World War II ===\nAs an infrastructure building, the central station was subject of heavy bombing during World War II. On 16 January 1945 the station was hit in a severe air raid on the city. The western station building was completely destroyed and never rebuilt, while the eastern entrance building was heavily damaged and the platform halls were partially collapsed. The tracks were littered with bomb craters and the signal boxes were partially destroyed by the bombing.\n\n===Reconstruction after 1945 ===\n[[File:Zu den Bahnsteigen MD Hbf.JPG|thumb|Entrance hall]]\nAt the end of March 1946, the restoration of the electrification had been completed on the rail networks in the [[Soviet occupation zone]]. Then, the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] military authorities then demanded the removal of the overhead line equipment and the transfer of the electrical rolling stock as [[War reparations|reparations]] to the Soviet Union, which was partly returned in the early 1950s in need of repair. The rail network was then electrified for the third time, and electric train operation resumed in 1956. Reconstructed of the main station started in 1946, but the platform halls were omitted.\n\nIn 1974, the Magdeburg S-Bahn was established. More extensive alterations were made in 1984. After [[German reunification]] in 1992, platforms were lengthened to allow [[Intercity-Express]] operation. In 2003, the pedestrian tunnel was extended to connect the various platforms to an entrance on the western side of the station. The station was modernised again between 2008 and 2015 at a cost of about \u20ac300 million.\n\n==Train services==\nThe following services currently call at the station:<ref>[http://kursbuch.bahn.de/hafas/kbview.exe/dn?st_name=Magdeburg+hbf&st_filter=&cat_name=&searchmode=station&mainframe=result&orig=sS&dosearch=1&oblig_st=1&submitButton=Suche+starten Timetables for Magdeburg Hbf station] {{in lang|de}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable vatop\"\n! Line\n! Train Type\n! Route\n! Operator\n! Frequency\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|IC|55|IC}}\n| [[Intercity (Deutsche Bahn)|Intercity]]\n| ''[[K\u00f6ln Hauptbahnhof|K\u00f6ln Hbf]] \u2013 [[Wuppertal Hauptbahnhof|Wuppertal Hbf]] \u2013 [[Dortmund Hauptbahnhof|Dortmund Hbf]] \u2013 [[Hamm (Westfalen) station|Hamm (Westfalen)]] \u2013 [[Hannover Hauptbahnhof|Hannover Hbf]] \u2013 [[Braunschweig Hauptbahnhof|Braunschweig Hbf]] \u2013 Magdeburg \u2013 [[Halle (Saale) Hauptbahnhof|Halle (Saale) Hbf]] \u2013 [[Leipzig/Halle Airport station|Leipzig/Halle Airport]] \u2013 [[Leipzig Hauptbahnhof|Leipzig Hbf]] \u2013 [[Dresden Hauptbahnhof|Dresden Hbf]]''\n| [[DB Fernverkehr]]\n| Every 2 hours\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|IC|56|IC}}\n| [[Intercity (Deutsche Bahn)|Intercity]]\n| ''[[Norddeich Mole railway station|Norddeich Mole]] \u2013 [[Emden Hauptbahnhof|Emden Hbf]] \u2013 [[Oldenburg (Oldenburg) Hauptbahnhof|Oldenburg Hbf]] \u2013 [[Bremen Hauptbahnhof|Bremen Hbf]] \u2013 [[Hannover Hauptbahnhof|Hannover Hbf]] \u2013 [[Braunschweig Hauptbahnhof|Braunschweig Hbf]] \u2013 Magdeburg \u2013 [[Halle (Saale) Hauptbahnhof|Halle (Saale) Hbf]] \u2013 [[Leipzig Hauptbahnhof|Leipzig Hbf]]''\n| [[DB Fernverkehr]]\n| Every 2 hours\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|IC|56|IC}}\n| [[Intercity (Deutsche Bahn)|Intercity]]\n| ''[[Norddeich Mole railway station|Norddeich Mole]] \u2013 [[Emden Hauptbahnhof|Emden Hbf]] \u2013 [[Oldenburg (Oldenburg) Hauptbahnhof|Oldenburg Hbf]] \u2013 [[Bremen Hauptbahnhof|Bremen Hbf]] \u2013 [[Hannover Hauptbahnhof|Hannover Hbf]] \u2013 [[Braunschweig Hauptbahnhof|Braunschweig Hbf]] \u2013 Magdeburg \u2013 [[Brandenburg Hauptbahnhof|Brandenburg Hbf]] \u2013 [[Potsdam Hauptbahnhof|Potsdam Hbf]] \u2013 [[Berlin Hauptbahnhof|Berlin Hbf]] \u2013 [[Cottbus station|Cottbus Hbf]]''\n| [[DB Fernverkehr]]\n| 1x day\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|IC|56|IC}}\n| [[Intercity (Deutsche Bahn)|Intercity]]\n| ''[[Leipzig Hauptbahnhof|Leipzig Hbf]] \u2013 [[Leipzig/Halle Airport station|Leipzig/Halle Airport]] \u2013 [[Halle (Saale) Hauptbahnhof|Halle (Saale) Hbf]] \u2013 Magdeburg \u2013 [[Stendal station|Stendal]] \u2013 [[Wittenberge station|Wittenberge]] \u2013 [[Schwerin Hauptbahnhof|Schwerin Hbf]] \u2013 [[Rostock Hauptbahnhof|Rostock Hbf]] \u2013 [[Warnem\u00fcnde station|Warnem\u00fcnde]]''\n| [[DB Fernverkehr]]\n| 1x day\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RE|1}}\n| [[Regional-Express]]\n| ''Magdeburg \u2013 [[Brandenburg Hauptbahnhof|Brandenburg Hbf]] \u2013 [[Potsdam Hauptbahnhof|Potsdam Hbf]] \u2013 [[Berlin Hauptbahnhof|Berlin Hbf]] \u2013 [[Erkner station|Erkner]] \u2013 [[F\u00fcrstenwalde (Spree) station|F\u00fcrstenwalde (Spree)]] \u2013 [[Frankfurt (Oder) station|Frankfurt (Oder)]] (\u2013 [[Cottbus station|Cottbus Hbf]])''\n| [[DB Regio Nordost]]\n| 1x per hour\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RE|6}}\n| [[Regional-Express]]\n| ''Magdeburg \u2013 [[Haldensleben station|Haldensleben]] \u2013 [[Oebisfelde station|Oebisfelde]] \u2013 [[Wolfsburg Hauptbahnhof|Wolfsburg Hbf]]'' \n| [[DB Regio S\u00fcdost]]\n| 4x per day\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RE|10}}\n| [[Regional-Express]]\n| ''Magdeburg - [[Stendal station|Stendal]] - [[Salzwedel station|Salzwedel]] - [[Uelzen station|Uelzen]]''\n| [[DB Regio S\u00fcdost]]\n| Every 2 hours\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RE|11}}\n| [[Regional-Express]]\n| ''Magdeburg - [[Halberstadt station|Halberstadt]] - [[Thale Hauptbahnhof|Thale Hbf]]''\n| [[Transdev Sachsen-Anhalt]]\n| 1x per hour\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RE|13}}\n| [[Regional-Express]]\n| ''Magdeburg - [[Dessau Hauptbahnhof|Dessau Hbf]] - [[Leipzig Hauptbahnhof|Leipzig Hbf]]''\n| [[DB Regio S\u00fcdost]]\n| Every 2 hours\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RE|14}}\n| [[Regional-Express]]\n| ''Magdeburg - [[Dessau Hauptbahnhof|Dessau Hbf]] - [[Lutherstadt Wittenberg Hauptbahnhof|Lutherstadt Wittenberg Hbf]] - [[Falkenberg (Elster) station|Falkenberg (Elster)]]''\n| [[DB Regio S\u00fcdost]]\n| Individual services\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RE|20}}\n| [[Regional-Express]]\n| ''Magdeburg - [[Stendal station|Stendal]] - [[Salzwedel station|Salzwedel]] - [[Uelzen station|Uelzen]]''\n| [[DB Regio S\u00fcdost]]\n| Every 2 hours\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RE|21}}\n| [[Regional-Express]]\n| ''Magdeburg - [[Halberstadt station|Halberstadt]] - [[Goslar station|Goslar]]''\n| [[Transdev Sachsen-Anhalt]]\n| Every 2 hours\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RE|30}}\n| [[Regional-Express]]\n| ''Magdeburg - [[Halle (Saale) Hauptbahnhof|Halle (Saale) Hbf]]''\n| [[DB Regio S\u00fcdost]]\n| 1x per hour\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RB|31}}\n| [[Regionalbahn]]\n| ''Magdeburg - [[Halberstadt station|Halberstadt]] - [[Blankenburg (Harz) station|Blankenburg (Harz)]]''\n| [[Transdev Sachsen-Anhalt]]\n| Every 2 hours\n|-\n| {{Bahnlinie|RB|36}}\n| [[Regionalbahn]]\n| ''Magdeburg - [[Haldensleben station|Haldensleben]] - [[Wolfsburg Hauptbahnhof|Wolfsburg Hbf]]''\n| [[DB Regio